[SPEAKER_05]: how we're getting started in Medford.

76
00:05:12,915 --> 00:05:21,320
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'll just, as you know, I have two colleagues, if you will, Jill and Anne, who are on the line, who just introduced themselves.

77
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:24,542
[SPEAKER_05]: So they may add on at the end, if there's anything I missed.

78
00:05:25,542 --> 00:05:27,043
[SPEAKER_05]: I'll just start out introducing myself.

79
00:05:27,764 --> 00:05:28,704
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm Christina Elaine.

80
00:05:28,764 --> 00:05:31,906
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm a Medford resident since 2020.

81
00:05:32,106 --> 00:05:35,108
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm a longtime, or I mean, my whole life, Massachusetts resident.

82
00:05:36,448 --> 00:05:41,795
[SPEAKER_05]: And I currently work as a project manager in biotech and previously in global health.

83
00:05:42,436 --> 00:05:50,347
[SPEAKER_05]: I know nothing or very little about matters of, you know, the climate from a technical perspective of climate change.

84
00:05:51,609 --> 00:06:00,975
[SPEAKER_05]: And I say that because I think that's maybe an important thing to know about Mothers Out Front is that it's an organization that is, you know, kind of encompassing and welcoming everyone.

85
00:06:02,196 --> 00:06:13,764
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, I think really, if I can put it this way from like, almost like the moral perspective of, you know, we really want to come together to take action that will be good for our children, for all the children, everyone's children.

86
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:19,778
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'm here as a Medford resident and as a new sort of volunteer with Mothers Out Front.

87
00:06:19,898 --> 00:06:23,460
[SPEAKER_05]: I became connected with the organization in early 2022.

88
00:06:24,281 --> 00:06:28,484
[SPEAKER_05]: I believe the organization has existed for about 10 years, however.

89
00:06:28,524 --> 00:06:38,871
[SPEAKER_05]: So there's kind of a long history already in track record of Mothers Out Front working at national, state, and local levels in local municipalities, really making a difference.

90
00:06:39,932 --> 00:06:43,274
[SPEAKER_05]: The way that they do this is primarily through grassroots organizing.

91
00:06:44,385 --> 00:06:52,527
[SPEAKER_05]: I just would like to read to you a few things from their website that I think really resonate with me about what the organization is all about.

92
00:06:53,307 --> 00:07:02,549
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's a nonprofit organization that was founded on the conviction that there's no more powerful force for change than mothers that are mobilizing to protect their children.

93
00:07:03,390 --> 00:07:10,091
[SPEAKER_05]: So we are united in our mission and our urgency to come together for climate and racial and social justice.

94
00:07:11,411 --> 00:07:13,832
[SPEAKER_05]: Through grassroots organizing, we seek

95
00:07:14,183 --> 00:07:19,125
[SPEAKER_05]: to move leaders, to ensure a healthy environment for all of our children.

96
00:07:20,285 --> 00:07:24,667
[SPEAKER_05]: We are an inclusive movement where our mother's voices are front and center.

97
00:07:26,787 --> 00:07:34,990
[SPEAKER_05]: We believe that we have impact because we have a strong community and that's built on kindness, mutual respect, and also on collaboration.

98
00:07:35,871 --> 00:07:41,113
[SPEAKER_05]: And in all we do, we keep our mission of a livable climate for all children at the center of our work.

99
00:07:42,891 --> 00:07:48,734
[SPEAKER_05]: Lastly, we focus resources in communities suffering injustice from racism, fossil fuels, and climate change.

100
00:07:50,295 --> 00:07:55,838
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's kind of some overarching description of how Mothers Out Front conceives itself.

101
00:07:58,219 --> 00:08:08,365
[SPEAKER_05]: There are activities and groups that are at national level, state level, and I think at least 10 states, and then in many municipalities here in Massachusetts.

102
00:08:09,844 --> 00:08:15,146
[SPEAKER_05]: So just to maybe switch gears from Mothers Out Front in general to the Medford group.

103
00:08:16,486 --> 00:08:24,689
[SPEAKER_05]: Mothers Out Front has not had a chapter in Medford, but we are seeking to start one and have started some work to form one.

104
00:08:26,069 --> 00:08:33,512
[SPEAKER_05]: We came together as a small group at the end of 2022, last year, around the event of a pumpkin smash.

105
00:08:34,327 --> 00:08:43,369
[SPEAKER_05]: which is an event to raise awareness of composting and how that can have a benefit and play a role in climate action.

106
00:08:44,229 --> 00:08:51,531
[SPEAKER_05]: And also at the same time, promote healthy soils and many activities that extend from that.

107
00:08:52,531 --> 00:09:01,133
[SPEAKER_05]: So this event was convened on November 5th in collaboration with the West Medford Community Center with Lisa Crossman there to host the Pumpkin Smash.

108
00:09:01,791 --> 00:09:15,499
[SPEAKER_05]: And that took place on November 5 and we convened a small group of volunteers here in Medford who were interested in helping to organize that worked with the West Medford Community Center, and we were able to come together on November 5 to smash a lot of pumpkins.

109
00:09:17,235 --> 00:09:20,577
[SPEAKER_05]: in various fun, family-friendly, destructive ways.

110
00:09:22,158 --> 00:09:27,622
[SPEAKER_05]: We were able to record 59 participants who attended from the community.

111
00:09:28,703 --> 00:09:36,268
[SPEAKER_05]: We counted 110 pumpkins that were smashed in this activity over the course of about two and a half hours, and that generated

112
00:09:36,968 --> 00:09:47,711
[SPEAKER_05]: 1500 pounds of compostable material, which was hauled away by our partner Garbage to Gardens, who may be familiar to you in Medford, as a curbside composting service provider.

113
00:09:47,731 --> 00:09:57,673
[SPEAKER_05]: And we also had the support of 30 youth volunteers as well, who helped to manage the different tools that were being used to smash these pumpkins.

114
00:09:58,333 --> 00:10:08,817
[SPEAKER_05]: We also were, you know, very grateful and excited to see Mayor Lungo Cohn attend, as well as Medford City Council member Richard Caraviello.

115
00:10:10,398 --> 00:10:20,401
[SPEAKER_05]: So now in 2023, there's a kind of a core group of us who came together for that pumpkin smash who are interested in continuing in Medford and to build and grow our movement.

116
00:10:21,142 --> 00:10:21,962
[SPEAKER_05]: We're very

117
00:10:23,086 --> 00:10:36,998
[SPEAKER_05]: excited and actively seeking, you know, to make connections in the quite extensive kind of ecosystem of practitioners in Medford, including you know I'm very much led by the city, working on energy and the environment.

118
00:10:38,713 --> 00:10:55,125
[SPEAKER_05]: And we are likely to continue working with the West Medford Community Center who are very interested in doing another pumpkin smash they saw a lot of benefits to raising the visibility and profile of the West Medford Community Center at that time through this activity and we see a lot of potential to continue working together and to

119
00:10:56,586 --> 00:11:15,479
[SPEAKER_05]: likely continue to raise awareness of composting, but perhaps to further our focus on activities that are related to that, which haven't been defined yet, but certainly could include ways that composting could be used, such as in gardening or other kinds of planting, but also extending to food security as well.

120
00:11:16,620 --> 00:11:18,862
[SPEAKER_05]: So we are just kind of getting started.

121
00:11:19,382 --> 00:11:20,343
[SPEAKER_05]: We're a nascent group.

122
00:11:20,523 --> 00:11:21,084
[SPEAKER_05]: We are

123
00:11:23,141 --> 00:11:37,786
[SPEAKER_05]: Working closely with West Medford Community Center, but looking to to connect with others in Medford to partner, where we might have mutual interests or complimentary capabilities.

124
00:11:41,500 --> 00:12:04,750
[SPEAKER_05]: The last thing I wanted to tell you is that just the small group of us who've come together, when we talk about kind of what brings us to this work, some of the things that we have in common that have been shared are our commitment to taking concrete action for climate, for climate action, also working locally, very locally here in Medford specifically, and also in finding and building community while we're doing that.

125
00:12:06,111 --> 00:12:10,993
[SPEAKER_05]: So to me, this is kind of the essence of Mothers Out Front and the power of the grassroots organizing.

126
00:12:12,697 --> 00:12:14,238
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think I'll stop there.

127
00:12:14,278 --> 00:12:22,983
[SPEAKER_05]: Those are some of the main things that I wanted to tell you, but I would invite my colleagues, Jill and Ann, to add on to this presentation if they would like to add anything.

